From 271fcf46eef43443fddb79091c33a2dbfda50a5a Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: =?UTF-8?q?Eric=20Meadows-J=C3=B6nsson?=
 <eric.meadows.jonsson@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 28 Apr 2026 22:31:54 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] Bound decimal casting to mitigate exponent amplification

Mitigates GHSA-rhv4-8758-jx7v ("decimal exponent amplification"), where
compact inputs like `1e1000000` could force the Decimal library into
multi-second expansions during arithmetic, parsing, normalization, and
formatting. Ecto guards its cast boundary so untrusted input can no
longer materialize pathological decimals via changesets.

`Ecto.Type.cast/2` for `:decimal` now delegates through a private
`cast_decimal/2` helper that, when the upstream Decimal library exports
the bounded `cast/2` and `parse/2` APIs, threads `:max_digits` and
`:max_exponent` into the parser. When the running Decimal version
predates those APIs, casting falls back to the previous unbounded
behaviour so existing deployments keep working.

Defaults to Postgrex-compatible limits (`max_digits: 147_455`,
`max_exponent: 131_071`). Operators can override globally via:

    config :ecto, :decimal_cast_options, max_digits: ..., max_exponent: ...

Schema fields can opt into per-field limits with the new `:max_digits`
and `:max_exponent` field options on `:decimal` columns. When set, the
field is compiled into a private `Ecto.Type.ParameterizedDecimal`
parameterized type whose `type/1` reports `:decimal` and which
delegates `load`, `dump`, and `equal?` to the built-in decimal type;
this works transparently inside `{:array, :decimal}` and other
composites. Decimal options are validated at compile time (and at cast
time for the global config) and must be non-negative integers or
`:infinity`; supplying them on non-decimal fields raises as before.

Inputs that exceed the configured limits cast to `:error` rather than
returning an over-large `Decimal`, matching Ecto's existing convention
for invalid casts.
